A shape like this.Â 

![](data:image/png;base64,)

The shape is not difficult to get. A couple of scale and extrude with a cylinder can get this.Â 

![](data:image/png;base64,)

The secondary shape is easy as well. Just extrude the faces and mortify vertices with transform tool, plus collapsing the bottom face, we'll get this.Â 

![](data:image/png;base64,)

The hard part of this mesh is the side part converging bevels, as the bevel geo cannot go upward or downward to keep the round bevel of cylinder unaffected.Â 

![](data:image/png;base64,)

As always, we work on one unit and duplicate it around.Â 

![](data:image/png;base64,)

We first try bevel just the shape without letting the bevel geo to go anywhere else.Â 

![](data:image/png;base64,)

We have a mess both at the top and the bottom part of the bevel.Â 

So we try to let the bevel geo to go sideway.Â 

![](data:image/png;base64,)

We only get a mess at the bottom part of the bevel. We choose this route and manually clean up the bottom part.Â 

We delete any unusable geo.Â 

We rebuild the geo by reconnect the parallel edges with multi-cut tool, and eyeball the converging point in the middle.Â 

![](data:image/png;base64,)

But when smoothed, the distance between vertices are too large, causing the vertices to move a lot.Â 

![](data:image/png;base64,)

So we add extra geo to help holding the shape.Â 

![](data:image/png;base64,)

But even then, we still have relatively large movement of vertices when smoothed.Â 

![](data:image/png;base64,)

So we can move the arrow geo down, so that there are a couple of horizontal lines to help fighting the vertice movement.Â 

![](data:image/png;base64,)

Then we duplicate this unit around to get the whole mesh.Â
